# syntax/ — compile-time / syntax-error golden batch

One self-contained `.sbl` per compile-time error code. Each program is the
minimal source that makes Macro SPITBOL raise exactly that error during
**compilation** (not execution), so these are **Golden** cases, never SelfCheck:
a syntax error aborts the compile, the program never runs, and the process exits
non-zero (231 on the reference build). The discriminating signal is the
`... : error NNN -- ...` line in the compiler's output, which is why each case
needs a captured `.expected` rather than an in-program assertion.

Every trigger here was validated against the reference `sbl` binary built from
the same `spitbol/x64` source as the Windows port — all 20 fire the intended
code with zero mismatches.

