| file                 | code | message                                      |
|----------------------|------|----------------------------------------------|
| namereq212.sbl       | 212  | value used where name is required            |
| badcont214.sbl       | 214  | bad label or misplaced continuation line     |
| duplabel217.sbl      | 217  | duplicate label                              |
| dupgoto218.sbl       | 218  | duplicated goto field                        |
| missop220.sbl        | 220  | missing operator                             |
| missopnd221.sbl      | 221  | missing operand                              |
| lbracket222.sbl      | 222  | invalid use of left bracket                  |
| comma223.sbl         | 223  | invalid use of comma                         |
| rparen224.sbl        | 224  | unbalanced right parenthesis                 |
| rbracket225.sbl      | 225  | unbalanced right bracket                     |
| norparen226.sbl      | 226  | missing right paren                          |
| gotorparen227.sbl    | 227  | right paren missing from goto                |
| gotorbrkt228.sbl     | 228  | right bracket missing from goto (direct goto)|
| arrbracket229.sbl    | 229  | missing right array bracket                  |
| illchar230.sbl       | 230  | illegal character (0x01 in source)           |
| badnum231.sbl        | 231  | invalid numeric item                         |
| strquote232.sbl      | 232  | unmatched string quote                       |
| gotofield234.sbl     | 234  | goto field incorrect                         |
| include285.sbl       | 285  | include file cannot be opened                |
| undeflabel286.sbl    | 286  | function call to undefined entry label       |

## Minting the goldens (Windows, as usual)

These need `.expected` files captured on the target build. Same procedure as the
goto/trap goldens — from inside the test project, never the solution root:

```powershell
cd SpitbolTests
$env:SPITBOL_UPDATE_GOLDEN = "1"
dotnet test --filter "DisplayName~syntax"
Remove-Item Env:\SPITBOL_UPDATE_GOLDEN
```

Then re-run without the env var to confirm green. Place `syntax.filter` so the
harness picks it up for these cases (per-directory, like `assert.inc` is copied).

## Two things to confirm on first capture

1. **Filename in the error line.** The captured line reads
   `<file>(line,col) : error NNN -- ...`. On the reference binary, invoking with a
   bare filename (cwd = case dir, the same working-dir rule the I/O fixtures use)
   yields just `strquote232.sbl(2,16) : ...` — no absolute path — so the golden is
   portable. If your runner passes an absolute path instead, the path gets baked
   into `.expected` and the case becomes machine-specific. If so, either switch the
   runner to a relative name for these, or add a path-stripping substitution (see
   note 2).

2. **The `(line,col)` position is baked in.** Whole-line-drop filtering can't strip
   it, so the position lives in the golden. That's fine for frozen files (it's
   deterministic), but it's the reason the deferred **OutputNormalizer substitution
   filter** matters: once it lands, a substitution like
   `s/\([0-9]+,[0-9]+\)/(L,C)/` (and an optional leading-path strip) lets you
   re-capture position-independent goldens. Until then, don't edit these `.sbl`
   files after capture — adding a line shifts every position and invalidates the
   golden.

## Reference: raw report shape (strquote232.sbl)

```
macro spitbol version 4.0f              <- dropped (version)
x86-64  Mon Jun 15 18:47:49 2026        <- dropped (volatile timestamp)
                              page 1    <- dropped (page header)
1       start   output = "open          <- kept (source listing)
             	         !               <- kept (caret)
strquote232.sbl(2,16) : error 232 -- syntax error: unmatched string quote   <- kept (the assertion)
```

## Still unresolved (carried over, NOT in this batch)

Triggers I could not pin to a simple, reliable source program:

- **215** undefined or erroneous entry label
- **216** missing end line
- **233** invalid use of operator — note: this is the build's *catch-all* for many
  malformed goto/operator constructs, so a clean isolated trigger is awkward (most
  "obvious" malformed gotos resolve to 233 rather than the specific goto codes).
- **247** invalid control statement
- **219** empty goto field — on this build `:()` resolves to **212**
  (name-required) rather than 219, so 219 appears unreachable here; worth a source
  dive next session to confirm.
